name: Diethyl 3,4-dimethylthieno[2,3-b]thiophene-2,5-dicarboxylate
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-3904
Reason: 3,4-dimethylthieno[2,3-b]thiophene-2,5-dicarboxylate has a melting point that is influenced by several structural components. The basic unit for comparison can be 2,3-dichlorobenzene, which has a melting point of -109.4 degrees Celsius. The introduction of two additional phenyl groups increases the melting point due to the increase in molecular weight and rigidity of the structure. Each phenyl group may add approximately +30 to +50°C due to the enhancement of π-π interactions and overall molecular rigidity. Additionally, the methyl groups contribute to the melting point due to their effect on the crystal lattice, estimated at around +5 to +10°C each. The carboxyl group introduces a hydroxyl group, which can participate in hydrogen bonding, raising the melting point by approximately +5 to +10°C. The thienyl group introduces a rigid structure, estimated at around +20 to +30°C. The dimethyl group reduces the melting point due to the reduced symmetry and increased molecular volume, estimated at around -10 to -5°C.
